Which would make more sense, planning your monthly budget off your desired income or current income? Trying to train at your desiredÂ fitness level is like spendingÂ money based on your desired income. Sure it may work for a little, but eventually it's going to catch up with you.Â 

My college coach Marcus O'Sullivan would always tell us, your race times should dictate your training paces, not the other way around. What he meant by this is you should never calculate your training paces off a goal race time, but instead always calculate your training paces off a recent race.

All too often I see runners sayingÂ if "I can only get my daily running pace down to XX I'll be able to hit my goal race time." Don't force the pace. Let it come naturally. A well designed trainingÂ plan will increaseÂ your running pace by properly manipulatingÂ volume, density and frequency of the workouts, not just simplyÂ telling you to run faster. Train smarter, not harder.Â 

Try these tips:Â 

âœ”There is a differenceÂ betweenÂ "5k pace" and "goal 5k pace." 5k pace is the pace you can run a 5k today and goal 5k pace is your desired 5k pace. Make sure your training plan distinguishes between the two. When in doubt, start off at your current 5k pace and pick up the pace as you feel comfortable.Â 

âœ”Only worry about your pace for two or three runs per week. The rest run by effort and don't get hung up with that pace, it really doesn't matter as much as you think.Â 

âœ”Reassess your training paces after each race. If you run a huge PR, it's time to adjust your training paces (tempo, threshold, recovery, etc)Â accordingly.

âœ”Use a training zone calculator like the one on my website (https://www.runyourpersonalbest.com/training-zones) to calculate training paces.

