Back in February I compiled a list of running goals I had wanted to accomplish in my 20s but never did.

I realized that if I trained for an even harder event, like training to qualify for Boston Marathon (sub 6:52 mile for 26.2 miles), I'd naturally achieve the other goals I had set.

Well, I've hit the first one.

âœ… Break a 1:40:00 half marathon

At the end of May, I declared I was going to try to break the 1:40 mark in 3 months time. At the time, I was at 1:44:29.

Back in August I ran a 1:42:00 half marathon and didn't know if I'd be able to break the 1:40 mark with just a month left.

I added in a ton of plyometrics, mile repeats, and some strength and conditioning that I'd let fall by the wayside.

But the key... was the taper.

I hadn't taken any real breaks from running since starting in February.

I took a 12 day taper. Meaning that after my last long run of 20 miles, I pulled back my mileage for the next 12 days to let my body recover from the constant pounding I'd put it through.

During the taper, I ate 100% plant based, hydrated, and learned how to bake bread so I wouldn't lose my mind.

Then today, I put one mile after another together, resulting in a finishing time of 1:39:49.

Now we rest, reset, and set our sights on the next goal.

